<section class="sec reveal" id="qbo-feat-bills-definition" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">In plain terms</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">What a QuickBooks Online bill is, plainly.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>A bill in QuickBooks Online is how you record money you owe a vendor <em>before</em> you pay it. You enter the vendor, the amount, the terms, and a due date, and assign the cost to the right account in your chart of accounts. The moment you save the bill, QuickBooks posts the amount to <a href="/glossary/accounts-payable/">Accounts Payable</a> &mdash; a liability account &mdash; and it sits there as an open payable until you pay it.</p>
      <p>When you do pay, you record the payment <em>against that bill</em>. That&rsquo;s the step that matters most: paying a bill clears it from Accounts Payable and reduces cash, so the obligation and the payment are linked as one event. If instead you record the payment as a separate expense and leave the bill open, you&rsquo;ve counted the same cost twice &mdash; once as the bill, once as the expense &mdash; and the bill stays on your A/P aging forever. Matching payments to bills is what keeps payables accurate.</p>
      <p>The <em>A/P aging</em> report is the payoff. It lists every open bill grouped by how overdue it is &mdash; current, 1&ndash;30 days, 31&ndash;60, and so on &mdash; so you can see exactly what you owe and when it&rsquo;s due, prioritize payments, and time them to terms. We describe QuickBooks Online&rsquo;s behavior as it actually works &mdash; we don&rsquo;t claim capabilities the feature doesn&rsquo;t have, and the actual processing of bill payments (and any fees) is Intuit&rsquo;s or a third party&rsquo;s, not ours.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

